    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Prior to the establishment of a city fire department in 1854, volunteer fire companies did the work of putting out fires in Ann Arbor, Michigan. One of these, the Ann Arbor Fire Co. No. 2, was organized in 1837. This later became Eagle Fire Company No. 2. The names of other companies included the Defiance Hood and Ladder Company and the Mayflower Fire Engine Company. The companies continued to do their work up into the 1880s.</p>
      <p>In the later part of the nineteenth century, the fire department also had responsibility for administering poor relief in the city.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The record group includes an early minute book of the fire department as well as minute books of various volunteer fire companies in the city. There are, in addition, scattered administrative records, including records of fires in the city, 1899-1962, and records of the poor relief administered by the department. These poor relief volumes include the name of the recipient, the amount, and the items purchased. Also included are the names of the individuals who funded the relief fund.</p>
    </scopecontent>
